# Orchestrate GitHub PRs review pipeline (Stage 6)

**Inputs**:
- The GitHub repo (currently `qualabs/sgai-for-mpeg-dash`) at run time
  via `gh pr list/view`. The orchestrator does not read a local cache
  of PRs — it always queries GitHub fresh.
- `.env.agent` at the project root. Required keys:
  - `TRUSTED_GH_USERS` — comma-separated GitHub logins that allow the
    full auto cycle (D2). Reused from Stage 5; no Stage-6-specific
    knob.
  - Optional `NOTEBOOK_ID` — passed through to `analyze-pr` when a
    keyword in the PR body or diff trips the detector (D6).
- The repo working tree (`context/`, `context-analysis/`, `output/`,
  `output-analysis/`, `.project/`, `CLAUDE.md`, `README.md`) — used
  by `analyze-pr` for content / convention / scope / downstream
  grounding.
- Invocation flags (parsed from the command line):
  - `--dry-run` (default) — produce all artefacts under
    `output-github-prs/pr-<N>/` but do NOT call `gh pr comment`,
    `gh pr review`, or any label-applying `gh` command on GitHub.
  - `--live` — same as `--dry-run` PLUS post the drafted review and
    apply labels via `gh` (see `post-review.prompt`).
  - `--pr <N>` (optional, repeatable) — restrict the run to one or
    more explicit PR numbers (useful for re-runs / smoke tests).
    When absent, the orchestrator processes every PR surfaced by
    `detect-prs`.

**Output**:
- One `output-github-prs/pr-<N>/` subfolder per processed PR,
  containing:
  - `meta.md` — **regenerated every run** with a fresh snapshot of
    the PR (title, body verbatim, author, branches, additions /
    deletions, file list, labels, current state, comments timeline).
    No history; the file mirrors the PR's current state.
  - `cycle-<C>/triage.md` — always written for the current cycle.
  - `cycle-<C>/analyze.md` — always written for the current cycle.
  - `cycle-<C>/review.md` — the drafted review for the current
    cycle.
  Where `<C>` is the cycle index (`1` on first run, `2` after the
  author has pushed new commits or replied to a prior AI review,
  etc.) computed by `detect-prs.prompt`. Each cycle's artefacts
  live in their own subfolder, preserving the audit trail across
  re-runs.
- A single end-of-run **summary block on stdout** (delimited by
  `=== SGAI-PRS RUN SUMMARY ===` / `=== END SUMMARY ===`) listing
  counts, per-PR verdicts, cycle indices, labels applied, routing
  decisions, and the outsider attention list. The parent agent
  picks this block up and relays it to Nicolas on Telegram — the
  orchestrator itself never sends Telegram messages.

**Skip if**: never. The orchestrator is always invoked manually
(D7); it decides per-PR whether work is needed by reading the PR's
label set (see Step 1).

**Execution mode**: foreground, single subagent. NO nested
subagents (the parent agent that invokes this prompt is the only
delegation boundary). The orchestrator itself reads the per-step
prompts inline and applies them — there is no `claude -p` recursion.

**Default policy**: dry-run (D1). The orchestrator never posts to
GitHub unless `--live` is explicitly passed.

---

## Setup

1. Parse the invocation flags. If neither `--dry-run` nor `--live`
   appears, assume `--dry-run`. If both appear, abort with an error
   to stdout — the operator must pick one.
2. Source `.env.agent` at the project root. Parse
   `TRUSTED_GH_USERS` into a set. If the file is missing or the
   variable is empty, log a warning and treat the trusted set as
   empty (every author will be treated as an outsider).
3. Resolve the GitHub repo from `git remote get-url origin`
   (normalise to `<owner>/<repo>`). Log it as
   `[REPO=<owner>/<repo>]`.
4. Log a single mode line:
   `[MODE=<dry-run|live>] [TRUSTED=<comma-list>]`.

## Pipeline

For each step below, log:
`[STAGE-6 <step> pr=<N>] <one-line status>`.

### Step 1 — Detect PRs to process

Apply the body of `prompts/6-github-prs/detect-prs.prompt`. Result:
an array of `{number, title, body, author, created_at, updated_at,
labels, base_ref, head_ref, additions, deletions, changed_files,
is_draft, mergeable, raw_lang_hint, cycle_count}` records, filtered
to **open, non-draft** PRs whose label set contains NONE of:

- `pr:ai-reviewed`
- `pr:ai-needs-review`
- `pr:ai-conversation-cap-hit`

`detect-prs` ALSO drops PRs that have reached the anti-loop cap
(D5 — `cycle_count >= 4`): it applies the
`pr:ai-conversation-cap-hit` label in `--live` mode and excludes
the PR from the returned set. The orchestrator never sees those
PRs in the loop below.

If the invocation passed `--pr <N>` one or more times, restrict the
result to those numbers regardless of label state (the operator is
explicitly re-targeting). The cap (D5) still applies on a forced
re-run — `detect-prs` will refuse to return a PR at
`cycle_count >= 4` even when explicitly listed.

Log: `[STAGE-6 detect] <count> PR(s) to process: [<N1>@cycle<C1>, <N2>@cycle<C2>, ...]`.
If `count == 0`, jump straight to the summary block.

### Step 2 — Per-PR loop

For each PR record from Step 1, in numerical order. Let `C =
pr.cycle_count` (computed by `detect-prs`; always `>= 1` and `<= 3`
for any PR that survived Step 1).

#### 2.0 — Regenerate `meta.md`

BEFORE invoking any of the per-step prompts, regenerate the PR's
`meta.md` snapshot so the cycle subfolders sit alongside an
up-to-date context anchor. Fetch the PR with comments and metadata:

```bash
gh pr view <N> \
  --repo <owner>/<repo> \
  --json number,title,body,author,createdAt,updatedAt,state,labels,baseRefName,headRefName,additions,deletions,changedFiles,files,isDraft,mergeable,comments,reviews
```

Write `output-github-prs/pr-<N>/meta.md` (create the parent folder
if absent) using this exact shape:

````markdown
# PR #<N> — <title>

- **Number**: #<N>
- **URL**: https://github.com/<owner>/<repo>/pull/<N>
- **Author**: <login> (https://github.com/<login>)
- **Author trust**: trusted | outsider
- **Created**: <ISO timestamp>
- **Updated**: <ISO timestamp>
- **State**: open | closed | merged
- **Draft**: true | false
- **Base → Head**: `<baseRefName>` ← `<headRefName>`
- **Diff size**: +<additions> / -<deletions> across <changedFiles> file(s)
- **Mergeable**: <mergeable value>
- **Labels (current)**: <comma-separated list, or "(none)">

## Files touched

| Path | +Add | -Del | Change type |
|------|------|------|-------------|
| `<path>` | <n> | <n> | <ADDED|MODIFIED|DELETED|RENAMED> |
| ... | ... | ... | ... |

## Original body (verbatim)

> <body line by line, blockquoted — preserve markdown / fenced
> blocks as-is inside the blockquote prefix>

## Comments timeline

| # | Author | Date | Kind | Snippet (first 80 chars) |
|---|--------|------|------|--------------------------|
| 1 | <login> | <ISO> | issue-comment | "<first 80 chars of body>…" |
| 2 | <login> | <ISO> | review-summary | "..." |
| ... | ... | ... | ... | ... |

(If there are no comments and no reviews, write "(no comments
yet)" instead of the table. Merge issue-style comments and review
summary comments into a single chronological timeline; mark each
row's `Kind` so the reader can tell them apart.)

Last refreshed: <orchestrator run timestamp, ISO-8601>
````

`meta.md` is **always overwritten** on every run — there is no
history. It is the up-to-date snapshot the cycle subfolders point
back to. Author trust is resolved as `trusted` if `login ∈
TRUSTED_GH_USERS`, else `outsider`.

Log: `[STAGE-6 meta pr=<N>] regenerated meta.md (cycle=<C>)`.

#### 2.1 — Triage

Apply `prompts/6-github-prs/triage-pr.prompt` against the PR,
passing `cycle_count = C` as an input. Write the verdict to
`output-github-prs/pr-<N>/cycle-<C>/triage.md` (create the cycle
subfolder if absent). Capture the structured fields:
- `trusted`: boolean (`author ∈ TRUSTED_GH_USERS`?)
- `severity`: `cosmetic` | `spec-detail` | `requirements` |
  `architectural`
- `lang`: ISO-639-1 (`en`, `es`, `pt`, `fr`, `it`, `de`, …) with
  `en` as fallback if detection is inconclusive (D4)
- `cycle_count`: echo of `C` from `detect-prs` (no recomputation
  inside the triage prompt — `detect-prs` is the single source of
  truth for the cycle index, and applies the anti-loop cap D5
  before this step is reached).
- `files_touched`: array grouping the diff paths by root
  (`context/`, `prompts/`, `context-analysis/`, `output/`,
  `output-analysis/`, `.project/`, other).
- `claim_summary`: 1–2 sentences summarising what the PR is
  trying to do (paraphrasing the PR body).

#### 2.2 — Analyse

Apply `prompts/6-github-prs/analyze-pr.prompt`, passing
`cycle_count = C`. The keyword detector runs inside that prompt
(D6); the orchestrator does not pre-filter. Write the result to
`output-github-prs/pr-<N>/cycle-<C>/analyze.md`. The analysis
covers the four axes (D13): content validation, convention
compliance, scope coherence, downstream impact.

This step runs **for every PR** (no flow gating like Stage 5).
Every PR review needs the four axes regardless of severity.

#### 2.3 — Propose review

Apply `prompts/6-github-prs/propose-review.prompt`, passing
`cycle_count = C`. Write the draft to
`output-github-prs/pr-<N>/cycle-<C>/review.md`. The prompt:
- Picks the verdict (`LGTM` / `SUGGESTIONS` / `BLOCKERS` /
  `SCOPE-MISMATCH`) from the analysis findings.
- Decides the routing (`comment` vs `review`) per D8, based on
  verdict and whether any finding is line-specific (D9).
- Injects the disclaimer blockquote if `severity ∈ {requirements,
  architectural}` (D3).
- Embeds a machine-readable metadata header for `post-review` to
  parse without re-reading the analysis.
- Appends the anti-loop marker `<!-- sgai-prs: ai-cycle -->`.

#### 2.4 — Post or hold

Decide whether to post:

- If `trusted == true` AND `--live` is set → apply
  `prompts/6-github-prs/post-review.prompt`. It reads the current
  cycle's draft at `output-github-prs/pr-<N>/cycle-<C>/review.md`,
  posts the review (top-level comment or formal `gh pr review
  --comment` with optional inline comments — see routing rules in
  `propose-review.prompt`), and applies the verdict-driven labels
  (D11): `pr:ai-reviewed` always, plus `pr:has-blockers` for
  `BLOCKERS` and `pr:scope-mismatch` for `SCOPE-MISMATCH`, plus
  `pr:needs-work` when `mergeable: false` AND verdict ∉
  {`BLOCKERS`, `SCOPE-MISMATCH`} (the mergeable signal is additive
  only when neither verdict-driven label already conveys "not
  ready to merge"). On success, mark this PR as `posted`.
- If `trusted == false` (outsider) → do NOT post regardless of
  mode. In `--live` mode, apply the `pr:ai-needs-review` label so
  Nicolas can see at a glance which PRs are waiting on his
  approval (D2). The review draft is still saved under
  `output-github-prs/pr-<N>/cycle-<C>/review.md`. Mark the PR as
  `needs-review`.
- If `--dry-run` → do not post and do not apply labels; mark the
  PR as `dry-drafted`.

**Critical safety rail (D12)**: `post-review.prompt` MUST refuse to
invoke `gh pr review --approve` or `gh pr review --request-changes`
or `gh pr merge` under any circumstances. The pipeline only posts
comments / `--comment` reviews. Approval and merge are exclusively
human decisions. If the orchestrator observes a draft or routing
that requests approve / request-changes, abort the post step for
that PR and surface it in the summary block under a `failed:`
section.

### Step 3 — Summary block

After the loop, emit to stdout:

```
=== SGAI-PRS RUN SUMMARY ===
mode: <dry-run|live>
repo: <owner>/<repo>
processed: <count>
  - <N>: cycle=<C> verdict=<V> mergeable=<true|false> reason=<token> routing=<comment|review> severity=<S> lang=<L> trusted=<bool> state=<posted|needs-review|dry-drafted>
  - ...
cap-hit (D5 anti-loop, dropped before triage):
  - <N>: <title> by <author> (cycle_count=<C>)
  - ...
needs-review (outsiders awaiting Nicolas decision):
  - <N>: cycle=<C> verdict=<V> mergeable=<true|false> <title> by <author>
  - ...
labels applied (live mode only):
  - <N>: [pr:ai-reviewed, pr:has-blockers?, pr:scope-mismatch?, pr:needs-work?]
  - ...
=== END SUMMARY ===
```

If counts are zero in any subsection, emit `(none)` rather than
omitting the heading — the parent agent's regex relies on the
section being present.

## Notes for future cron integration (D7)

Manual invocation today. When the trigger flips to cron:

- The cron job should pass `--dry-run` first, save the summary
  block to a fresh log, and only escalate to `--live` if the
  operator reviewed the dry run.
- Or skip the dry-run gating and run `--live` directly — but only
  after `TRUSTED_GH_USERS` is wide enough that the
  `pr:ai-needs-review` queue stays manageable.
- Either way, the cron driver writes the summary block to a file
  that the Telegram-notify hook tails — same parent-agent contract
  as Stage 5.
